06435nam a22007095i 9780226014241DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226014241  a(DE-B1597)568252  a(OCoLC)1233041575  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPS151b.S76 2014 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.9/928702aA Story Larger than My Own :bWomen Writers Look Back on Their Lives and Careers /ced. by Janet Burroway. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tThe Older Writer in the Underworld -- tOn Craft -- tThe Ratio Is Narrowing -- tParsing Ambition -- tMothers and Daughters -- tThe Offices of My Heart -- tWorking on the Ending -- tThe Potholder Model of Literary Ambition -- tBreaking the Final Taboo -- tPassing It On -- tMetamorphosis: From Light Verse to the Poetry of Witness -- tOn Certainty -- tSplitting Open: Some Poems on Aging -- tOld Woman, or Nearly So Myself: An Essay in Poems -- tPublic Appearances -- tSay Yes -- tBoys and Girls -- tThe Stories from Which I Come -- tWhat I Know -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCONTRIBUTORS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1955, Maxine Kumin submitted a poem to the Saturday Evening Post. “Lines on a Half-Painted House” made it into the magazine—but not before Kumin was asked to produce, via her husband’s employer, verification that the poem was her original work. Kumin, who went on to win the Pulitzer Prize for poetry, was part of a groundbreaking generation of women writers who came of age during the midcentury feminist movement. By challenging the status quo and ultimately finding success for themselves, they paved the way for future generations of writers. In A Story Larger than My Own, Janet Burroway brings together Kumin, Julia Alvarez, Jane Smiley, Erica Jong, and fifteen other accomplished women of this generation to reflect on their writing lives. The essays and poems featured in this collection illustrate that even writers who achieve critical and commercial success experience a familiar pattern of highs and lows over the course of their careers. Along with success comes the pressure to sustain it, as well as a constant search for subject matter, all too frequent crises of confidence, the challenges of a changing publishing scene, and the difficulty of combining writing with the ordinary stuff of life—family, marriage, jobs. The contributors, all now over the age of sixty, also confront the effects of aging, with its paradoxical duality of new limitations and newfound freedom. Taken together, these stories offer advice from experience to writers at all stages of their careers and serve as a collective memoir of a truly remarkable generation of women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aWomen authors, AmericanvLiterary collections. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  awomen writers, female authors, maxine kumin, saturday evening post, pulitzer prize, groundbreaking generation, midcentury feminist movement, us history, american literature, julia alvarez, jane smiley, erica jong, essays, poems, poetry, collection, writing lives, commercial success, literary criticism, career, subject matter, crises of confidence, publishing scene, family, marriage, jobs, womens issues, aging, newfound freedom, collective memoir.1 aAlvarez, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtwood, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlais, Madeleine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Rosellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc